segment.target:
As *Commander* you are the only person who can access this terminal.
////
Moving the ship is essential for **travelling to other planets** and could be useful for getting rid of hunters.
////
To go to a planet you need to **know the heading and the quantity of fuel required**. These two pieces of information can be obtained from the *Astro Terminal*. With this information, someone must first fill the combustion chamber with the appropriate amount of fuel. Then, set the Daedalus on the correct path and start the journey!
////
If the job has been done properly, the Daedalus will put itself into a planet's orbit, which can then be explored by the crew and new resources obtained!

{orientation, select,
                  north {West :left::left::left: **North** :right::right::right: East}
                  south {East :left::left::left: **South** :right::right::right: West}
                  east {North :left::left::left: **East** :right::right::right: South}
                  west {South :left::left::left: **West** :right::right::right: North}
                  other {The Daedalus is currently heading towards : **{orientation}**.}
}

In order to find a planet to explore, you must firstly *run a scan* which will find a maximum of {max_planets} planets. The details of the planet scan are private and unique to every character.
////
Once a planet has been found and chosen, you should then communicate the *bearing and fuel requirement* for the journey to the crew. This allows the *Commander* to pilot the Daedalus towards the chosen planet.
////
When the Daedalus has arrived and is in orbit, it is impossible to scan to search for other planets. However, you can *scan the planet* you are orbiting to obtain additional GeoInfo. This information will be useful for the expedition team, who will be able to better prepare their exploration.
////
To leave orbit, the Commander in charge must give this order from the Command Terminal.

Here you can carry out research to benefit the entire crew. There are two ways to collaborate: bring items to the laboratory to unlock new research, or advance research that is already underway.
//
Some items will unlock the appropriate research while in the room's shelf, while others must be held in hand to render their research visible.
//
A lone crewmember, even if they have the appropriate skills, will have difficulty successfully completing research. If you advance research more than once in a row, your efficiency will decrease. Alternating work with your crewmates is the key!

